Check out the [.filter](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/filter) method.


    var a = [ {id:1, latlong:[...]} , {id:2, latlong:[...]} , ... ];
    console.log(a.filter((item) =&gt; item.id === 2));

You can use array `filter` which will return an array of objects. Then use index (example `[0]` in this code) to retrieve the first object

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var a = [{
      id: 1,
      latlong: &#39;&#39;
    }, {
      id: 2,
      latlong: &#39;&#39;
    }];

    let newVal = a.filter(e =&gt; e.id === 2)[0];
    console.log(newVal)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

To find a single entry, there&#39;s the [`.find`][1] method:

    const a = [ {id:1, latlong:[...]} , {id:2, latlong:[...]} , ... ];
    const el = a.find((item) =&gt; item.id === 2);
    console.log(el);

  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/find

